 I? Yes, trudging along again as in the old days with John, in the woods of Arcady, under a salmon sky.

“Well,” I said gaily, “what were you writing about last night, John? Your study window was simply blazing.”

“Mountains,” he answered.

The Bera Range, an erection of veined stone and shaggy firs, rose before me in all its power and pride. The splendid news made my heart pound, and I felt that I could now, in my turn, afford to be generous. I begged my friend not to impart to me a